      "subsections": [
        {
          "title": "Formules Fondamentales",
          "elements": [
            {
              "type": "theorem-box",
              "content": [
                "$\\cos(a-b) = \\cos a \\cos b + \\sin a \\sin b$",
                "$\\cos(a+b) = \\cos a \\cos b - \\sin a \\sin b$",
                "$\\sin(a+b) = \\sin a \\cos b + \\cos a \\sin b$",
                "$\\sin(a-b) = \\sin a \\cos b - \\cos a \\sin b$"
              ],
              "listType": "bullet"
            },
            {
              "type": "example-box",
              "preamble": "Calcul de $\\cos(\\frac{\\pi}{12})$",
              "content": [
                "On remarque que $\\frac{\\pi}{12} = \\frac{\\pi}{3} - \\frac{\\pi}{4}$.",
                "$\\cos(\\frac{\\pi}{3} - \\frac{\\pi}{4}) = \\cos \\frac{\\pi}{3} \\cos \\frac{\\pi}{4} + \\sin \\frac{\\pi}{3} \\sin \\frac{\\pi}{4}$",
                "$= \\frac{1}{2} \\cdot \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2} + \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\cdot \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2} = \\frac{\\sqrt{2} + \\sqrt{6}}{4}$."
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Formules de Duplication et Linéarisation",
      "subsections": [
        {
          "title": "Angle Double",
          "elements": [
            {
              "type": "property-box",
              "content": [
                "$\\cos(2x) = \\cos^2 x - \\sin^2 x = 2\\cos^2 x - 1 = 1 - 2\\sin^2 x$",
                "$\\sin(2x) = 2 \\sin x \\cos x$",
                "$\\tan(2x) = \\dfrac{2 \\tan x}{1 - \\tan^2 x}$"
              ],
              "listType": "bullet"
            },
            {
              "type": "method-box",
              "title": "Linéarisation (Carrés)",
              "listType": "numbered",
              "content": [
                ">>Pour intégrer ou primitive, il faut souvent linéariser.",
                "$\\cos^2 x = \\dfrac{1 + \\cos(2x)}{2}$",
                "$\\sin^2 x = \\dfrac{1 - \\cos(2x)}{2}$"
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "title": "Transformation en Tangente de l'arc moitié",
          "elements": [
            {
              "type": "theorem-box",
              "content": [
                "En posant $t = \\tan(\\frac{x}{2})$, on a :",
                "$\\cos x = \\dfrac{1-t^2}{1+t^2} \\quad ; \\quad \\sin x = \\dfrac{2t}{1+t^2} \\quad ; \\quad \\tan x = \\dfrac{2t}{1-t^2}$"
              ],
              "listType": "bullet"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Équations Trigonométriques",
      "subsections": [
        {
          "title": "Équation $a \\cos x + b \\sin x = c$",
          "elements": [
            {
              "type": "method-box",
              "title": "Méthode de l'angle auxiliaire",
              "listType": "numbered",
              "content": [
                ">>On factorise par $R = \\sqrt{a^2 + b^2}$.",
                "$a \\cos x + b \\sin x = R \\left( \\frac{a}{R} \\cos x + \\frac{b}{R} \\sin x \\right)$",
                "On cherche $\\alpha$ tel que $\\cos \\alpha = \\frac{a}{R}$ et $\\sin \\alpha = \\frac{b}{R}$.",
                "L'équation devient $R \\cos(x - \\alpha) = c$, soit $\\cos(x - \\alpha) = \\frac{c}{R}$."
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "practice-box",
              "statement": "Résoudre $\\cos x + \\sin x = 1$.",
              "solution": [
                "$a=1, b=1$, donc $R = \\sqrt{1^2+1^2} = \\sqrt{2}$.",
                "$\\sqrt{2} (\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} \\cos x + \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} \\sin x) = 1$",
                "$\\sqrt{2} (\\cos \\frac{\\pi}{4} \\cos x + \\sin \\frac{\\pi}{4} \\sin x) = 1$",
                "$\\cos(x - \\frac{\\pi}{4}) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} = \\cos \\frac{\\pi}{4}$",
                "Deux cas : $x - \\frac{\\pi}{4} = \\frac{\\pi}{4} [2\\pi]$ ou $x - \\frac{\\pi}{4} = -\\frac{\\pi}{4} [2\\pi]$.",
                "Solutions : $x \\equiv \\frac{\\pi}{2} [2\\pi]$ ou $x \\equiv 0 [2\\pi]$."
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}